<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,1729,2008]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1873,1899]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was originally described from a single specimen with R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1152,1178,1892,1906]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">4+5</subScript>
branched (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Shamshev, I. V." pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 61" refId="ref85321" refString="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Shamshev, I. V. (2012) World revision of Iteaphila macquarti group (Diptera: Empididae). Zootaxa, 3561 (1), 1 - 61. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3561.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Sinclair &amp; Shamshev 2012</bibRefCitation>
). The above series represents a population characterized by an unbranched R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1196,1222,1928,1942]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">4+5</subScript>
and was originally considered a new species until the genitalia were more closely studied and compared (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Shamshev, I. V." box="[1124,1432,1945,1971]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 61" refId="ref85321" refString="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Shamshev, I. V. (2012) World revision of Iteaphila macquarti group (Diptera: Empididae). Zootaxa, 3561 (1), 1 - 61. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3561.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Sinclair &amp; Shamshev 2012</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 6A) to similar species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
